Wash and dry all produce. Preheat #oven{} to 400 degrees. Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Cut @Yukon Gold Potatoes{12%ounce} into bite-sized pieces. Add to another large pot with a large pinch @salt{} and enough water to cover by 1 inch. Bring to a boil and cook until just shy of tender, about ~{10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, cut @Green Beans{6%ounce} into 2-inch pieces. Once potatoes have cooked 10 minutes, add green beans to pot and cook until tender, ~{4-5%minutes} more. Drain and return everything to pot. Meanwhile, trim, then thinly slice @Scallions{1} (we sent more), keeping greens and whites separate. Cut @Lemon{1} in half. Cut one half into wedges.

Combine @Panko Breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, 3/4 tsp @Fry Seasoning{1/2%tablespoon}, a drizzle of @Olive Oil{2%teaspoon}, and a pinch of salt and @Pepper{} in a small #bowl{}. Toss to combine. Rinse @Cod Fillets{11%ounce}, then pat dry with #paper towels{}. Season all over with salt, pepper, and another 3/4 tsp fry seasoning (you'll have some leftover). Place on a lightly oiled #baking sheet{}. Sprinkle panko mixture over tops of fillets, pressing to adhere.

Bake cod in oven until flesh is opaque and crumbs are golden brown, about ~{10%minutes}. Once water in first large pot is boiling, add @Corn on the Cob{2}. Cook until tender and bright yellow, ~{5-7%minutes}. Drain.

Add scallion whites and @Butter{1 1/2%tablespoon} to pot with potatoes and green beans. Return to stove over medium heat and toss until butter is melted. Squeeze in juice from lemon half and toss. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide cod and green bean and potato mixture between plates. Season corn with salt and add a small pat of @Butter{1/2%tablespoon} to each cob (we used 1/4 TBSP each). Sprinkle scallion greens over everything and serve with lemon wedges on the side for squeezing over.

> You don't get much more easy and breezy than corn on the cob, a jumble of potatoes and green beans, and a crunchy fish fillet. In fact, we'd like to declare this the unofficial weeknight meal of summer. Whether you're enjoying it by the seashore or on your backyard patio, it's a dish that's simple and carefree, the way our mood in the warmer months should be.